castAddBody.text: Watched Wall E with the family. It's insightful how in 2008 the dystopian "human hooked up to a screen" theme was tilted over splashy big corporations running a la Blade Runner instead of what is turning out to be 15 years later (subtle, unconscious addiction).
I remember the political angle of idiocracy, but I don't recall if there was any technological angle to it

On the same dystopian topic, I watched a video of Sabine Hossenfelder about how US committee were trying to figure out to future proof nuclear waste disposal sites. It turns out that one of the major concern was that humans of the future would just be dumb.
I think that the sudden acceleration of AI of the last months or so is going to completely change the game in terms of hopes and expectations for the next 50-100 years.

I wonder what happens to geniuses such as Byrner Hobart and Matt Levine with maturing LLMs. How the hell they produce so much content of such high quality god only knows. But, I wonder at what point AI is going to give the connecting-the-pieces and producing tools to more mediocre folks.
In addition to the API providers of these AI models, what kind of businesses are going to be created that capture the value of cheap productivization of ideas?
Perhaps a bundling cycle after the Cambrian explosion of models and "prompt helpers"? Is it going to be the usual compute-time IaaS platforms capturing the value here?
Robotics make a lot of sense as a value capture, as it's got an hardware component that continues to have distribution bottlenecks.
Are there any examples of two geographically adjacent competitors that benefits from mutual cooperation brokered by a neutral third party?
True, I don't know enough to know if trade agreements can be typically brokered by a third party country. Ideas?

What are other examples of practical outcomes of a successful business measured as an impact on those involved in building it (and immediately adjacent)?
I don't find the number of jobs created that far away from an ideal metrics, yet conditional to some qualities (perhaps your point)
Probably Pachinko would fit the bill
i'd rebalance toward caring about our RL neighbors and elderly. I haven't thought deeply enough to figure what powers you'd need to pull to achieve this.

Terraforming as in interplanetary colonization has always an element of resource extraction, first enough for survival then at scale. Terraforming as a set of actions to rebalance scarcity and demand of resources must prove its ground, all-in, in a small setting.

I think that high-entropy is a confusing term introduced in the essay by Scott. "universal culture" as the culture that adapts to the most convenient norms, technologies and tastes is what I get out of it. Stretching the definition, perhaps "high-free energy" society would be better?

Re:recent trends, they seem to me to be high "entalpy" rather than entropy, contributing yes to the total entropy of the system, but in a way that does not have the universal aspect Scott mentioned. Anyhow, thanks for surfacing that old post, lots to think about.

We moved to a small town in Italy for work reasons from the West Coast, and over the weekend we were in London, looked at each other in our eyes and thought: we gotta get out of there. Real life adaptation is really hard on kids, online friendships make it a bit easier on us very online adults, but not quite enough ...
I think about this a lot. Coming of age stories make us taste the seed of freedom, change, quintessential transformation we all have to go through at a certain age. But then we get stuck.
